On @realmoney Here is why I sold on the Fed rate cut rally in stocks this morning... Mar 03, 2020 | 11:10 AM EST DOUG KASS Out of SPY and QQQ I am calling an audible and I sold the balance of my (SPY) (at $310.85) and (QQQ) (at $217.65).

With the benefit of hindsight, yesterday's outsized and historic advance likely was discounting the Federal Reserve rate cut which was announced today. Again this might be too cute by half but I would not be surprised to see, at the very least, another test in the S&P futures

at around 3050 (55 handles below the current level). As I wrote earlier: "I am not sure whether this was a wise move from the standpoint of where stocks might be in several months but it's probably prudent in that I have "room to buy" on weakness (where I didn't before I sold),

in light of the magnitude of the gain off of Friday's lows and based on my expected S&P trading range of 2850-3300 (futures got to almost 3140 on the morning rip, reducing the reward vs. risk)." This takes my net long invested exposure way down from those elevated levels that

existed early this morning and, as mentioned in my Diary, provides me the ammunition to be more opportunistic - which is desirable in a regime of heightened volatility. A "TINA ('there is no alternative") Ripper" remains possible but, perhaps, not before some more testing

and filling. I fully plan to buy back at lower levels. Note: The sort of trading I have exhibited in the last few weeks is not for most investors. It is not easy and is filled with stress. It is my response to market conditions and my view that opportunistic trading is likely
a necessary reagent in order to deliver superior returns these days. @tomkeene @jimcramer @cnbcfastmoney @SquawkCNBC @saraeisen

You and your team are shortsighted. Lower interest rates are not a sign of strength, they are a sign of weakness. You and the Fed have failed to notice that European and Japanese central banks failed to stimulate economic growth, sapped the liquidity from their markets, and left
their economies buried in epic levels of debt that can never be repaid without destroying their currencies.

The Fed is now left with dropping rates back to zero or even below zero (which is no longer unthinkable for this bunch) or employing a variety of quantitative easing strategies that will monetize American financial markets just as the European Central Bank and Bank of Japan

monetized their respective markets over the last decade. Sadly, the Fed failed to notice that European and Japanese central banks failed to stimulate economic growth, sapped the liquidity from their markets, and left their economies buried in epic levels of debt that can never

be repaid without destroying their currencies. Even more sadly, American politicians will praise today’s interest rate cut because they are, with rare exceptions, economically illiterate and/or profoundly short-sighted. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney
